\def\workflowsblock{
  \flexblock{Workflows and Limitations}{
    \begin{columns}
      \begin{column}{.48\textwidth}
    Extract analysis histories into reusable workflows, previously had critical limitations.

    \begin{itemize}

      \item Static number of inputs. Common, relatively simple analyses in bioinformatics require running a variable number of inputs across identical processing steps (``mapping'')
      and then combining or collecting these results into a merged output (``reducing''). 

      
      \item Workflow engine planned out every job right at submission
      time (leaving little room for dynamic computation).
      Many requested advanced features such as pausing workflows,
      splitting inputs up into multiple datasets, and conditionals all
      require the re-evaluation of workflows overtime.
            
      \end{itemize}
    \end{column}
    \begin{column}{.48\textwidth}
      \begin{figure}
        \fleximage{1.00}{data_flow_cropped.png}
      \end{figure}
    \end{column}
  \end{columns}
  }
}

\def\collectionsblock{
  \flexblock{Dataset Collections}{
    \begin{columns}
      \begin{column}{.48\textwidth}
        \begin{figure}
          \fleximage{1.00}{cufflinks_workflow.png}
        \end{figure}
        Common RNA-Seq Galaxy workflow using the tuxedo suite
        updated to use dataset collections.
      \end{column}
      \begin{column}{.48\textwidth}

      Galaxy dataset collections allow gathering datasets into potentially nested hierarchies of lists and pairs and
      operating on them as units. Pre-existing Galaxy tools can be used without modification to ``map'' operations across
      dataset collections to produce new collections. Likewise tools that consume many datasets can be readily used to
      ``reduce`` these collections. For newly developed tools - a wide range of extensions to Galaxy tooling format exist
      to consume and produce dataset collections. In addition to presenting these additions to Galaxy, extensions to the
      workflow system to tie together these analyses and innovative UI elements such as the paired list dataset collection
      builder will be presented.
      \end{column}

    \end{columns}
  }
}

